<li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Eden, Colin (July 1988). "Cognitive mapping". <i><a href="/wiki/European_Journal_of_Operational_Research" title="European Journal of Operational Research">European Journal of Operational Research</a></i>. <b>36</b> (1): 1–13. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1016%2F0377-2217%2888%2990002-1">10.1016/0377-2217(88)90002-1</a>. <q>In the practical setting of work in with a team of busy managers cognitive mapping is a tool for building interest from all team members in the problem solving activity. [...] The cycle of <i>problem construction</i>, <i>making sense</i>, <i>defining the problem</i>, and declaring a <i>portfolio of solutions</i>, which I have discussed elsewhere (Eden, 1982) is the framework that guides the process of working with teams. Thus building and working with the cognitive maps of each individual is primarily aimed at helping each team member reflectively 'construct' and 'make sense' of the situation they believe the team is facing. (pp. 7–8)</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=European+Journal+of+Operational+Research&amp;rft.atitle=Cognitive+mapping&amp;rft.volume=36&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=1-13&amp;rft.date=1988-07&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2F0377-2217%2888%2990002-1&amp;rft.aulast=Eden&amp;rft.aufirst=Colin&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACognitive+map" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
